# dna_parser.exe
# Core engine for organism generation.
# DNA is a program written in a 4-letter alphabet (A, T, G, C)
# that encodes the instructions for building and maintaining
# every living thing that has ever existed on Earth.

# ============================================================
# THE CODE
# ============================================================
# Alphabet: A (adenine), T (thymine), G (guanine), C (cytosine)
# Base pairing: A-T (2 hydrogen bonds), G-C (3 hydrogen bonds)
# Structure: double helix, right-handed, 10 bp per turn, 3.4 nm pitch
# Total in human genome: ~3.2 billion base pairs
# Genes: ~20,000 (only ~1.5% of genome codes for proteins)
# The rest: regulatory sequences, transposons, structural DNA, "dark matter"

# ============================================================
# REPLICATION — Copying the program
# ============================================================
# Semiconservative: each strand serves as template for a new strand.
# Speed: ~1000 bp/second in humans, ~100,000 bp/second in bacteria
# Accuracy: 1 error per 10⁹ bases (with proofreading and repair)
#
# Replication fork:
#   Helicase → unwinds the double helix
#   Primase → lays down RNA primer
#   DNA Pol III → synthesizes new strand (5'→3' only)
#   Leading strand: continuous synthesis
#   Lagging strand: Okazaki fragments, later joined by ligase
#
# Telomeres: repetitive sequences at chromosome ends (TTAGGG in humans)
# Shorten with each division. Hayflick limit: ~50 divisions.
# This is the molecular clock of aging.

# ============================================================
# MUTATION — Bugs in the code
# ============================================================
# Types:
#   Point mutations: single base change
#     Silent: codes for same amino acid (redundancy of genetic code)
#     Missense: codes for different amino acid (sickle cell: GAG→GTG)
#     Nonsense: creates premature stop codon (truncated protein)
#   Insertions/Deletions: frameshift mutations (usually catastrophic)
#   Chromosomal: inversions, translocations, duplications
#
# Mutation rate: ~1-2 × 10⁻⁸ per base pair per generation (human)
# ~60-80 new mutations per person per generation
#
# Most mutations are neutral. Some are harmful. Rarely, one is beneficial.
# This is the raw material of evolution.
# Without bugs, there would be no updates.

# ============================================================
# GENE REGULATION — Running the right code at the right time
# ============================================================
# Every cell has the same DNA. A liver cell and a neuron
# differ not in their code but in which genes are expressed.
#
# Mechanisms:
#   Transcription factors: proteins that activate/repress genes
#   Enhancers/silencers: distant DNA sequences that modulate expression
#   Epigenetics: methylation and histone modification
#     (writing notes in the margins without changing the text)
#   microRNA: small RNA molecules that silence genes post-transcriptionally
#
# The genome is not a blueprint. It is a context-sensitive program.
# The same code produces a butterfly wing and a caterpillar leg
# depending on regulatory context.

# ============================================================
# CRISPR — Editing the program
# ============================================================
# Bacteria evolved CRISPR as an immune system against viruses.
# Doudna and Charpentier (2012) repurposed it as a gene editor.
# Nobel Prize 2020.
#
# Cas9 protein + guide RNA → cut DNA at specific location
# Cell's repair machinery → insert, delete, or replace sequence
#
# Applications: genetic diseases, agriculture, gene drives
# Ethical questions: germline editing, enhancement, consent
#
# For the first time, the organism can edit its own source code.
# /bin/dna_parser.exe now has a built-in text editor.

# ============================================================
# OUTPUT
# ============================================================
# Input: 3.2 billion base pairs
# Output: a human being
# Compilation time: ~9 months
# Runtime: ~80 years (varies)
# Known bugs: ~7,000 identified genetic diseases
# Self-modifying: yes (CRISPR, transposons, somatic mutation)
# Open source: yes (GenBank, since 1982)
